comment:
I think you should go a bit easy on the perpetrator here. In domestic abuse cases it is more than usual the perpetrator is suffering from personality disorders and perceives the world a bit different.

Perpetrators are prone to stress and they see who is right or wrong is not in the eyes of a calm person.

Their entire life may be held together by frantic attempts to make life make sense.

To an outsider with no experience it may seem like they do things deliberately and with cruelness, but the cruelness is rather lack of perspective or a limited set of options presented to them by their poor understanding of what is going on.

Nonetheless they make real harm and real damage.

We like to punish them and make them improve. The problem is changing the perception of who you are and what friends are for, is not fixed with traditional learning or guilt

This is not a crime by an ordinary person that exceeds the speed limit now and then. It is more like a personality that has complex issues. It is like shouting at diabetes.

Hating it and punishing it is therapy for us. To actually make a difference with an abuser, damage control is number one and then if possible a long and costly therapy where the patient is able to stay with the therapist long enough without quitting due to bad feelings or conflict.

If the perpetrator is fortunate to have professional therapy with an expert without quitting there is hope.

Take a look at "Dialectical Behavior Therapy - Dr. Fruzzetti" and imagine the complexity of living with a top model attractive bombshell or Superman who is not feeling well:

https://youtu.be/nFwAiO22g4Y
